    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-12-24T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-12-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="540"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d540">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/1–1049: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Mao Tse-tung</persName> to the
                        Appointed Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hurley</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Yenan</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-12-24">24 December,
                            1944</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Many thanks for your message which has been received. Preparations here for an
                    important conference are keeping General Chow En Lai very busy making it
                    difficult for him to get away. In our opinion the National Government has not
                    yet shown sufficient sincerity to justify carrying on negotiations on our five
                    point proposal. Our suggestion is that a conference be held in Yenan—Colonel
                    Barrett being present if possible. We send our best regards.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Mao Tze-tung</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
